            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this Spanish pension calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Spain’s public pension system is complex and changes over time.
                This calculator uses a simplified model based on current rules
                and OECD/Seguridad Social information to give you an approximate
                <strong>monthly state pension</strong> and the
                <strong>gap</strong> you may need to cover with private savings.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Contributory state pension (jubilación contributiva)</h3>
              <p>
                The main Spanish retirement benefit is the
                <em>contributory pension</em>, financed by Social Security
                contributions on your salary. The key drivers are:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Years of contributions</strong> to the Spanish system
                  (or credited via EU/bilateral agreements).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Contribution base</strong> – roughly your average
                  gross salary used to calculate contributions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Retirement age</strong> – whether you retire at the
                  legal age or earlier/later.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Simplified formula used in this tool
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  We approximate your gross monthly pension as:
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  \( \text{Pension} \approx \text{Average Contribution Base}
                  \times \text{Accrual Rate} \times \text{Age Factor} \)
                </p>
                <ul class="text-sm mt-2">
                  <li>
                    <strong>Accrual rate</strong> grows with years of
                    contributions, from 0% at 0 years up to 100% at 36+ years
                    (approximation of Spanish scales).
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Age factor</strong> is 1.0 at the normal retirement
                    age (67) and slightly lower if you retire earlier.
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <p>
                In reality, Spain uses a detailed formula based on your
                <strong>contribution bases over the last years</strong>, updated
                for inflation, and applies specific percentages for each year of
                contributions. Our model smooths these rules into an
                easy‑to‑understand estimate.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Non‑contributory pension (pensión no contributiva)</h3>
              <p>
                If you have
                <strong>little or no contribution history</strong> and limited
                income and assets, you may qualify for a
                <em>non‑contributory pension</em>. Key conditions typically
                include:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Being at or above the legal retirement age.</li>
                <li>
                  Having
                  <strong>at least 10 years of legal residence</strong> in Spain
                  (with some years immediately before the claim).
                </li>
                <li>Very low income and assets (household means‑testing).</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator only checks a
                <strong>basic residence condition</strong> and flags
                “<em>Possible</em>” or “<em>Unlikely</em>” eligibility. For an
                official decision you must apply through
                <a
                  href="https://www.seg-social.es"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >Seguridad Social</a
                >
                or your regional authority.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Private pension gap</h3>
              <p>
                Many retirees want a higher income than the state pension alone
                can provide. We compare your:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Target net retirement income</strong> (what you want
                  to live on each month), with
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Estimated state pension</strong> (gross, before tax
                  and health contributions).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The difference is the <strong>monthly gap</strong> that needs to
                come from:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Occupational or private pension plans (<em
                    >planes de pensiones</em
                  >),
                </li>
                <li>Investment portfolios, savings, rental income, etc.</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Private savings projection (simplified)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  We project your savings at retirement using compound interest:
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  \( \text{Future Savings} = S_0 (1+r)^n + C \times
                  \dfrac{(1+r)^n - 1}{r} \)
                </p>
                <ul class="text-sm mt-2">
                  <li>\( S_0 \) = current savings</li>
                  <li>\( C \) = monthly contribution × 12</li>
                  <li>\( r \) = expected annual return (e.g. 3%)</li>
                  <li>\( n \) = years until retirement</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="text-sm mt-2">
                  We then convert this pot into an indicative monthly income
                  using a simple annuity factor (e.g. 25 years in retirement).
                  This is only a rough guide.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Key Spanish pension rules to know</h2>
              <p>
                The exact rules change over time and can differ depending on
                your career path, sector, and whether you qualify for early or
                delayed retirement. As of recent reforms, some important points
                are:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Minimum contribution period:</strong> you generally
                  need at least 15 years of contributions to qualify for a
                  contributory pension.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Full pension:</strong> requires a much longer
                  contribution history (around 36–37 years depending on the
                  calendar year).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Normal retirement age:</strong> gradually increasing
                  to 67, with the possibility to retire earlier if you have a
                  long contribution record.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>EU coordination:</strong> if you worked in other
                  EU/EEA countries or Switzerland, those years can often be
                  totalised to meet minimum periods.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p>For detailed, up‑to‑date rules, always check:</p>
